properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 15 at 4:47PM CDT by NWS Aberdeen SD
properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...James River near Stratford.

* WHEN...Until further notice.

* IMPACTS...At 16.0 feet, 137th Street and 140th Street are flooded

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 3:45 PM CDT Saturday the stage was 14.6 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 3:45 PM CDT Saturday was 14.6 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise to a crest of 15
feet early Sunday morning. The river is expected to fall
below flood stage early Monday morning. Additional rises are
expected later in the week by Friday morning.
- Flood stage is 14.0 feet.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

rainfall continues.

* WHERE...A portion of Orange County in NY.

* WHEN...Until 645 PM EDT.

* IMPACTS...Minor flooding in low-lying and poor drainage areas.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 538 PM EDT, Doppler radar indicated heavy rain due to
thunderstorms. This will cause urban and small stream
flooding. Between 2 and 2.5 inches of rain have fallen.

over the area. This additional rain will result in minor
flooding.

Middletown, Howells, Scotchtown, Mechanicstown, Slate Hill,
Circleville, Bullville and New Hampton.

until at least 30 minutes after the storm has passed.

Do not drive through flooded roads or underpasses. Avoid low lying
areas near small streams.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 15 at 4:34PM CDT by NWS Shreveport LA
properties.description:
At 433 PM CDT, Doppler radar was tracking a strong thunderstorm near
Waldo, moving northeast at 10 mph.

HAZARD...Winds in excess of 40 mph and nickel size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor damage to outdoor objects is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
McNeil, Willisville, Lamartine, Young, College Hill and Waterloo.
properties.instruction:
If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with this storm.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.

This storm may intensify, so be certain to monitor local radio
stations and available television stations for additional information
and possible warnings from the National Weather Service.

A Severe Thunderstorm Watch remains in effect until 1000 PM CDT for
southwestern Arkansas.

Waters from Pensacola FL to Pascagoula MS from 20 to 60 NM...

At 430 PM CDT, severe thunderstorms capable of producing wind gusts
in excess of 50 knots were located along a line extending from near
Mary Esther to 13 nm southeast of Oriskany Reef to 46 nm southwest
of Okaloosa Deep Water Reef, moving east at 40 knots.

HAZARD...Waterspouts, wind gusts in excess of 50 knots, and small
hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Waterspouts can easily overturn boats and create locally
hazardous seas. Boats could suffer significant structural
damage in high winds. Small craft could capsize in suddenly
higher waves.

Locations impacted include...
Oriskany Reef.
properties.instruction:
Boaters should seek safe harbor immediately until these storms pass.
Wind gusts in excess of 50 knots, waterspouts, small hail, high
waves, dangerous lightning, and heavy rain are possible with these
storms.

Frequent lightning is occurring with these storms. If caught on the
open water stay below deck if possible, keep away from ungrounded
metal objects.

properties.description:
At 510 PM EDT, Doppler radar was tracking a strong thunderstorm over
Kingston, moving north at 5 mph.

HAZARD...Winds in excess of 30 mph and half inch hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor damage to outdoor objects is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
Kingston, Saugerties, Rhinebeck, Hurley, Woodstock, Red Hook, West
Hurley, Saugerties South, Port Ewen, Kenneth L Wilson Campground,
Lake Katrine, Phoenicia, Mount Tremper, Rosendale, Marbletown,
Veteran, Germantown, Tivoli, Centerville and Rolling Meadows.

This includes Interstate 87 between exits 19 and 20.
properties.instruction:
If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with this storm and may lead to
localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with this storm.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.

This storm may intensify, so be certain to monitor local radio
stations and available television stations for additional information
and possible warnings from the National Weather Service.

properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Wind Advisory, northwest winds 20 to 30 mph

freezing temperatures as low as 31 possible.

* WHERE...Portions of north central and northwest Illinois and
east central Iowa.

* WHEN...For the Wind Advisory, from noon Sunday to 7 PM CDT
Monday. For the Freeze Watch, from Sunday evening through
Monday morning.

* IMPACTS...Gusty winds could blow around unsecured objects.
Tree limbs could be blown down and a few power outages may
result. Frost and freeze conditions could kill crops, other
sensitive vegetation and possibly damage unprotected outdoor
plumbing.
properties.instruction:
Use extra caution when driving, especially if operating a high
profile vehicle. Secure outdoor objects.

Take steps now to protect tender plants from the cold. To prevent
freezing and possible bursting of outdoor water pipes they should
be wrapped, drained, or allowed to drip slowly. Those that have
in-ground sprinkler systems should drain them and cover above-
ground pipes to protect them from freezing.

properties.areaDesc: Benson, ND; Cavalier, ND; Eddy, ND; Nelson, ND; Ramsey, ND; Towner, ND
properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 15 at 3:11PM CDT by NWS Grand Forks ND
properties.description:
Overland flooding may increase in coverage through this weekend
into next week across the Devils Lake Basin. A cooler pattern is
expected through this weekend, however daytime temperatures will
still rise above freezing allowing for additional melt to occur.
Temperatures begin to warm again next week accelerating the melt
of any lingering snowpack. If overland flooding occurs it may
eventually lead to impacts such as road closures, washouts, and
other snowmelt impacts.

Should a flood warning be issued for your area, see the warning
statement for information on how to prepare and mitigate flood-
related impacts.

If you have any questions, contact the NWS Grand Forks office at
701-772-0720.

You can follow us on the web at: weather.gov/fgf and on Facebook
at:
www.facebook.com/NWSGrandForks and on Twitter at: @NWSGrandForks.

034.

* HUMIDITY...Relative humidity in the 17 to 22 percent range.

strong winds, low relative humidity, and warm temperatures can

properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 15 at 12:17PM MDT by NWS Boise ID
properties.description:
Melting of the lower and mid elevation snowpack will continue
as a warming trend occurs through Sunday. This will increase the
risk of flooding along creeks, streams, and rivers through
early in the week. The risk of sheet flooding in flat low-lying
terrain and poor drainage areas will increase as well.

If there is deep snow in your area, clear snow, ice and debris
from culverts and other flow paths to allow runoff to flow away
from buildings and other vulnerable infrastructure. Move deep snow
away from the foundations of buildings and move equipment, and
livestock out of poorly drained or low lying areas.

Stay tuned to the latest hydrologic forecasts.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 15 at 11:21AM MDT until April 16 at 12:00PM MDT by NWS Grand Junction CO
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt continues.

* WHERE...A portion of east central Utah, within Grand County, along
the Dolores River from the UT/CO stateline to the confluence with
the Colorado River.

* WHEN...Until noon MDT Sunday.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. Streams
continue to rise due to excess runoff from snowmelt. Low-water
crossings may be inundated with water and may not be passable.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 1120 AM MDT, gauge reports indicated snowmelt. Flooding is
ongoing or expected to begin shortly in the warned area.
- This includes the following streams and drainages...
Beaver Creek, Granite Creek, Colorado River, Waring Canyon,
Dolores River and Fisher Creek.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
mainly rural areas of Southeastern Grand County
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles. Do not attempt to cross flooded roads.
Find an alternate route.

Please report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and request they pass this information to the National
Weather Service when you can do so safely.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 15 at 11:20AM CDT until April 17 at 7:45PM CDT by NWS Aberdeen SD
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt continues.

* WHERE...A portion of west central Minnesota, including the
following county, Traverse.

* WHEN...Until 745 PM CDT Monday.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. Several
structures are flooded and some sand bagging operations are
continuing. Streams continue to rise due to excess runoff from
earlier rainfall.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 1117 AM CDT, emergency management continued to report
widespread flooding from snowmelt in the warned area due to
snow melt. Flooding is already occurring, with numerous
county and township roads barricaded due to flooding.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Wheaton, Browns Valley, Dumont, Tintah, Mud Lake Landing,
Collis, Silver Bridge, Immanuel Church, Siloah Country
Church, Halls Landing, Trinity Lutheran Country Church,
Rainbow Island, Lake Traverse, Traverse Country Park and
northeastern Lake Traverse Reservation.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Please report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and request they pass this information to the National
Weather Service when you can do so safely.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 15 at 11:15AM CDT until April 16 at 1:00PM CDT by NWS Bismarck ND
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt will continue.

* WHERE...Central and portions of western North Dakota, including
the James River Valley.

* WHEN...Until 100 PM CDT Sunday /noon MDT Sunday/.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. Numerous roads
remain closed due to flooding.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 1101 AM CDT /1001 AM MDT/, Snowpack has been soaking into
the ground and the upper portions of soils are becoming
saturated. Areas that have appreciable snowpack remaining
will see additional runoff in the coming days as the ponding
water eventually makes its way through frozen culverts and
into the waterways. In the Prairie pothole region, ponds and
sloughs may see water rise enough to run over roads.
Throughout the warned area, county and township roads may
become covered in water due to high water and plugged
culverts. Mainly rural areas in the affected counties will be
affected, but towns and cities may also experience localized
flooding issues.
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Please report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and request they pass this information to the National
Weather Service when you can do so safely.

properties.instruction:

jams. Never drive through flooded roads or around closed road
barricades. The barricades are there for your safety due to the
potential for ice jam releases or continued flooding.

* WHERE...A portion of south central Arizona, including the
following county, Maricopa.

* WHEN...Until 500 PM MST Friday Apr 21.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of unbridged crossings across the Salt River
upstream of Tempe Town Lake is occurring.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 504 AM MST, upstream releases from Roosevelt Dam and
Stewart Mountain Dam continue, and water releases from
Granite Reef Dam remain steady. These releases are impacting
low water crossings upstream of Tempe Town Lake with several
road closures.
- Unusually strong currents and debris will affect recreational
interests in Tempe Town Lake.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Unbridged river crossings such as McKellips and Gilbert
Roads, and gravel pit operations along the Salt River between
Granite Reef Dam and Tempe Town Lake.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

properties.description:

* WHAT...Flooding caused by upstream dam release continues.

* WHERE...A portion of south central Arizona, including the
following county, Maricopa.

* WHEN...Until 500 PM MST Friday Apr 21.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of unbridged crossings across the Salt and Gila
Rivers is occurring.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 504 AM MST, water releases from Tempe Town Lake continue.
These releases are still impacting low water crossings in the
warned area.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
El Mirage Road near Avondale, agricultural and industrial
interests within the Salt and Gila river beds.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles. Do not attempt to walk through flood
waters. Stay away or get swept away!

properties.description:

* WHERE...Sturgeon River near Nahma Junction.

river. This may include...parts of the Flowing Well Campground
downstream of gauge site and the tenmile rapids canoe launch
upstream of the gauge site.

- At 8:45 AM EDT Friday the stage was 9.3 feet.

- Action stage is 8.0 feet.
- Flood stage is 10.0 feet.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 15 at 7:48AM EDT until April 16 at 11:26AM EDT by NWS Raleigh NC
properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Neuse River Near Clayton.

* WHEN...Until late tomorrow morning.

* IMPACTS...At 9.0 feet, Minor flooding begins. Minor overflow
occurs on both banks. Water reaches the edge of the Neuse River
Greenway trail.
At 10.0 feet, Upstream of the gage site, the Neuse River Greenway
at Covered Bridge Road begins to flood.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 7:15 AM EDT Saturday the stage was 8.6 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise above flood stage
late this morning to a crest of 9.5 feet this afternoon. It
will then fall below flood stage late this evening.
- Flood stage is 9.0 feet.
- Flood History...No available flood history.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

properties.areaDesc: Florence, WI; Forest, WI; Langlade, WI; Lincoln, WI; Marathon, WI; Marinette, WI; Menominee, WI; Oconto, WI; Oneida, WI; Outagamie, WI; Portage, WI; Shawano, WI; Vilas, WI; Waupaca, WI; Waushara, WI; Winnebago, WI; Wood, WI
properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 15 at 5:02AM CDT by NWS Green Bay WI
properties.description:
An unseasonably warm airmass allowed for a quick snowmelt last week,
with only far northern Wisconsin still reporting snow on the
ground.  Due to the anomalously high snowpack that was in place, a
lot of water will be flowing through the rivers into next week.

Minor to moderate flooding is expected to continue along streams,
rivers, and other low-lying areas that regularly experience spring
snowmelt flooding. Flows will continue to increase as well,
especially on the Menominee.

Additional precipitation today into early next week will likely bring
new and/or continue or enhance ongoing flooding concerns, especially
for area rivers that are currently near/at/above flood stage or are
susceptible to low-land flooding.

If you live in or commute through an area that is currently flooding
or has previously experienced spring melt flooding, expect impacts
to continue and/or prepare for potential impacts.

The next update to this outlook is expected by 8:00 AM CDT
Monday April, 17, 2023.

Weather Service when you can do so safely.

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 14 at 3:14PM PDT until April 21 at 3:00PM PDT by NWS Reno NV
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by upstream dam release and snowmelt is
occurring.

* WHERE...A portion of western Nevada along the East Walker River
below Bridgeport Reservoir, including the following county, Lyon.

* WHEN...Until further notice. Prolonged flooding is likely.

* IMPACTS...Flooding is expected to impact East Walker Road and
other low lying areas. River or stream flows are elevated.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 305 PM PDT, Flooding will result in the advisory area from
an upstream dam floodgate release combined with increased
snowmelt.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
mainly rural areas of Southern Lyon County, including East
Walker Road.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

NWSheadline: FLOOD ADVISORY FOR EAST WALKER RIVER IN LYON COUNTY IN EFFECT UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE

properties.areaDesc: Lorain; Cuyahoga; Lake; Geauga; Ashtabula Inland; Medina; Summit; Portage; Ashtabula Lakeshore
properties.headline: Air Quality Alert issued April 14 at 3:07PM EDT by NWS Cleveland OH
properties.description:
An Air Quality Advisory for Ground Level Ozone has been issued by
the Northeast Ohio Areawide Coordinating Agency for Ashtabula,
Cuyahoga, Geauga, Lake, Lorain, Medina, Portage and Summit Counties.
The advisory is until midnight EDT Saturday night.

Air quality levels will be unhealthy for sensitive groups during
this period. If you are in the sensitive groups category of
children, the elderly and those with breathing difficulties, please
monitor your outdoor activity and check air quality readings at
airnow.gov. Additionally, sign-up at enviroflash.info for text
alerts regarding air quality.

To help our region reduce air pollution:

*Drive less: bike, walk, use transit, work from home, combine trips
*Visit gohiocommute.com/noaca - Find a smarter way to travel!
*Don't idle - Turn off your engine
*Refill your tank after sunset
*Wait to mow the lawn

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 14 at 8:05AM MDT until April 17 at 4:12PM MDT by NWS Albuquerque NM
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt continues.

* WHERE...Pecos River above Pecos.

* WHEN...Until Monday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...At 5.0 feet, THE FAST FLOW IN THE UPPER PECOS IS A
THREAT TO PROPERTY DUE TO THE EFFECTS OF BANK EROSION ALLOWING
RIVER WATER TO APPROACH HOMES AND CABINS NEAREST THE RIVER.
PRIVATE BRIDGES OVER THE UPPER PECOS COULD LOCALLY AGGRAVATE
FLOODING AS DEBRIS ACCUMULATES ALONG THE UPSTREAM SIDES OF
BRIDGES. FURTHER WATER LEVEL RISES MAY MAKE PRIVATE BRIDGES UNSAFE
TO CROSS AND ISOLATE RESIDENTS.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 7:00 AM MDT Friday the stage was 4.0 feet.
- Forecast...The river will oscillate below flood stage with a
maximum value of 4.6 feet late Sunday evening.
- Action stage is 4.5 feet.
- Flood stage is 5.0 feet.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 13 at 7:00PM CDT until April 17 at 8:15PM CDT by NWS Aberdeen SD
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt continues.

* WHERE...A portion of northeast South Dakota, including the
following county, Day.

* WHEN...Until 815 PM CDT Monday.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, roads, and other
low-lying and flood-prone locations is occurring. Numerous roads
remain closed due to flooding. Expect many areas of slow moving or
standing water.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 652 PM CDT, emergency management reported snowmelt
flooding continues in the warned area. Flooding of numerous
county and township roads continues including 447th Avenue,
south of Waubay.
- The office of Day County Emergency Management asks travelers
to exercise caution and obey posted road closure and detour
signs.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Webster, Waubay, Bristol, Enemy Swim Housing, Roslyn,
Pierpont, Andover, Grenville, Butler, Lily, Holmquist,
Antelope Lake, Waubay Lake, Swan Lake, Minnewasta Lake, Rush
Lake, Opitz Lake, Waubay Wildlife Rec Area, Bitter Lake and
Blue Dog Lake.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Be especially cautious at night when it is harder to recognize the
dangers of flooding.

In hilly terrain there are hundreds of low water crossings which are
potentially dangerous in heavy rain. Do not attempt to cross flooded
roads. Find an alternate route.

Please report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and request they pass this information to the National
Weather Service when you can do so safely.

properties.description:
Warm temperatures over northern mountain snowpack are driving
rapid runoff. Creeks and rivers in the mountains will experience
rapid rises. Mountain roads may experience localized flooding.


HAZARD...Rising creeks and rivers. Possible localized flooding.

IMPACT...Potential for impassable roads at high elevations.

Locations impacted include...
All rivers and creeks in the Sangre de Cristo and Tusas mountains.
All northern tributaries of the Rio Grande.
properties.instruction:

drive through flooded roadways. Be wary of rock and mudslides in
steep locations.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 11 at 6:31AM CDT until April 15 at 7:00PM CDT by NWS Sioux Falls SD
properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Big Sioux River at Sioux Falls I-90.

* WHEN...Until Saturday evening.

* IMPACTS...At 15.0 feet, some farm buildings between Renner and
Sioux Falls are threatened by high water.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 6:00 AM CDT Tuesday the stage was 13.2 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 6:00 AM CDT Tuesday was 13.2 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise to a crest of 13.6
feet this evening. It will then fall below flood stage Friday
evening or night.
- Flood stage is 12.0 feet.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 11 at 4:56AM CDT until April 15 at 7:00PM CDT by NWS Milwaukee/Sullivan WI
properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Fox River near Berlin.

* WHEN...Until Saturday evening.

* IMPACTS...At 13.2 feet, There is minor flooding in the Berlin area
including in Riverside and Webster Street Parks in Berlin. This
level is about a 50 percent chance flood meaning there is a 50
percent chance in any given year of the river reaching this level.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 4:00 AM CDT Tuesday the stage was 13.1 feet.
- Bankfull stage is 12.0 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 4:00 AM CDT Tuesday was 13.2 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to fall below flood stage
early Saturday afternoon and continue falling to 12.7 feet
Monday evening.
- Flood stage is 13.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
13.2 feet on 02/22/1984.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

properties.areaDesc: East Baton Rouge, LA; Pointe Coupee, LA; West Feliciana, LA
properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 10 at 10:20AM CDT until April 22 at 7:00AM CDT by NWS New Orleans LA
properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Mississippi River At Red River Landing.

* WHEN...Until Saturday, April 22.

* IMPACTS...At 51.0 feet, All river islands along the reach from Red
River Landing to Baton Rouge will be inundated. Recreational camps
and river bottom farm land will be under water.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 9:00 AM CDT Monday the stage was 51.7 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 9:00 AM CDT Monday was 51.7 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise to a crest of 52.0
feet early Wednesday afternoon. It will then fall below flood
stage Saturday, April 22.
- Flood stage is 48.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
52.0 feet on 03/27/1882.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 10 at 9:08AM CDT until April 15 at 7:00PM CDT by NWS Sioux Falls SD
properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Rock River at Rock Rapids.

* WHEN...Until Saturday evening.

* IMPACTS...At 16.0 feet, the higher banks on the left side of the
river, and the lower banks on the right side, will begin flooding.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 8:15 AM CDT Monday the stage was 12.7 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise above flood stage
late this afternoon to a crest of 14.6 feet early Wednesday
afternoon. It will then fall below flood stage Friday
evening.
- Flood stage is 13.0 feet.
